NETL Cyclone data¶

This notebook builds off the NETL Cyclone KMeans example. We will apply hierarchical clustering to the NETL Cyclone data.

Cluster the outputs¶

We clearly need to standardize the outputs BEFORE we apply clustering. The two have orders of magnitudes differences and so mass will NOT be accounted for at all in any distance calculation!!!! We must remove the magnitude and scale effects!!!

We must decide if we should remove the skew before applying clustering!

Let's try multiple approaches to see the influence of the SKEW on the clustering results!

PREPROCESS - standardize only¶

In [18]:
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler
In [19]:
from sklearn.pipeline import Pipeline
In [20]:
stan_wflow = Pipeline( steps=[('std_scale', StandardScaler())])
In [21]:
output_stan_fit = stan_wflow.fit( output_df )

PREPROCESS - removing skew¶

We discussed multiple ways to remove skew last week. But we will only consider one for this example.

In [37]:
from sklearn.preprocessing import QuantileTransformer
In [38]:
qt_wflow = Pipeline( steps=[('std_scale', StandardScaler()),
                            ('qt', QuantileTransformer(output_distribution='normal')),
                            ('std_qt', StandardScaler())] )
In [39]:
output_qt_fit = qt_wflow.fit( output_df )

C:\Users\jyurk\anaconda3\envs\cmpinf2120\lib\site-packages\sklearn\preprocessing\_data.py:2667: UserWarning: n_quantiles (1000) is greater than the total number of samples (96). n_quantiles is set to n_samples.
  warnings.warn(
In [40]:
Y_qt = output_qt_fit.transform( output_df )
